    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-06-29T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-06-29T03:00:00-05:00" n="131"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d131">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002 Manchuria/122: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1"
                            type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-06-29T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >June 29, 1932—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 29—7:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>741. Following from American Consul General at Mukden: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“June 28, 5 p.m. Foreign Minister <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_HC4"
                                >Hsieh</persName> yesterday issued a second declaration regarding
                            taking over customs the important points of which were: <list>
                                <label>1.</label>
                                <item>The new state takes over customs and collection of all customs
                                    receipts, but in case it is impossible to collect at Dairen
                                    collection will be made at another place (presumably just
                                    outside leased territory).</item>
                                <label>2.</label>
                                <item>New régime again accepts responsibility for payment of
                                    proportionate share of receipts required for service of the
                                    foreign loans.</item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                        <p>It has been learned that all Japanese in Chinese customs at Antung have
                            resigned, though customs is still functioning. It is probable that they
                            will join service of the new régime. It is reported Antung customs was
                            taken over at 10 a.m. today by intervention of Japanese troops.”</p>
                        <p>“June 28, midnight. Newchwang customs yesterday was taken over forcibly
                            by a new superintendent of customs (a Manchu), a Japanese adviser and
                            considerable body of police. The reason for this action is said to be
                            the dismissal of <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_FJ1"
                                >Fukumoto</persName>.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
